05857nam a22008895i 9780520972087DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019021813  a97805209720877 a10.1525/97805209720872doi  a(DE-B1597)541606  a(OCoLC)1099539303  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aKF8745.S67 4aKF8745.S67 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a347.73/26342231 aLima, Lázaro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeing Brown :bSonia Sotomayor and the Latino Question /cLázaro Lima. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Studies Now: Critical Histories of the Present ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOverview -- tIntroduction. On Being Brown in the Democratic Commons -- tPart I. A latina for the nation -- t1. Sonia Sotomayor and "the Latino Question" -- t2. Sonia Sotomayor's Elusive Embrace -- tPart II. Losing Sonia Sotomayor -- t3. Sonia Sotomayor, the Mediapheme -- t4. Sonia Sotomayor and Other States of Debt -- tCoda. Thinking Otherwise: Sonia Sotomayor and the Emergence of Latino Legal Thought -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeing Brown: Sonia Sotomayor and the Latino Question tells the story of the country's first Latina Supreme Court Associate Justice's rise to the pinnacle of American public life at a moment of profound demographic and political transformation. While Sotomayor's confirmation appeared to signal the greater acceptance and inclusion of Latinos-the nation's largest "minority majority"-the uncritical embrace of her status as a "possibility model" and icon paradoxically erased the fact that her success was due to civil rights policies and safeguards that no longer existed. Being Brown analyzes Sotomayor's story of success and accomplishment, despite seemingly insurmountable odds, in order to ask: What do we lose in democratic practice when we allow symbolic inclusion to supplant the work of meaningful political enfranchisement? In a historical moment of resurgent racism, unrelenting Latino bashing, and previously unimaginable "blood and soil" Nazism, Being Brown explains what we stand to lose when we allow democratic values to be trampled for the sake of political expediency, and demonstrates how understanding "the Latino question" can fortify democratic practice. Being Brown provides the historical vocabulary for understanding why the Latino body politic is central to the country's future and why Sonia Sotomayor's biography provides an important window into understanding America, and the country's largest minority majority, at this historical juncture. In the process, Being Brown counters "alternative facts" with historical precision and ethical clarity to invigorate the best of democratic practice at a historical moment when we need it most.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHispanic American judgesvBiography. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aaccomplishment.  aamerican public life.  acivil rights policies.  ademocratic practice.  afirst latina supreme court justice.  agreater acceptance.  ahistorical moment.  aicon.  ainclusion of latinos.  ainsurmountable odds.  ameaningful political enfranchisement.  aminority majority.  apossibly model.  aprofound demographic transformation.  aresurgent racism.  asafeguards.  asuccess.  asymbolic inclusion.  auncritical embrace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEB